Authentication System
Citizens & Providers — Firebase Auth
Firebase email/password sign-in
On every API call, api.js retrieves the current Firebase JWT with auth.currentUser.getIdToken() and sends it as Authorization: Bearer <token>
Falls back to localStorage.getItem('auth_token') if Firebase is unavailable
Backend FirebaseAuthMiddleware verifies the token via Firebase Admin SDK and attaches firebase_uid to the request
Controllers call resolveUser() / resolveProvider() which look up the User/Provider by firebase_uid
Also sends X-Mock-Role header (from localStorage.user.role) for dev convenience
Admins — Direct MongoDB Auth
POST /api/admin/login with email + password
Backend checks bcrypt hash stored on User document
Returns a session token stored as admin_token on the User doc
Frontend stores token in localStorage as auth_token
AdminAuthMiddleware reads the token from the Authorization header and matches it against admin_token in the database
Route Guards (Frontend)
ProtectedRoute component checks:

Is user authenticated?
Does user role match allowedRoles?
If requireApproved is set, is provider status approved?
Pending providers → /pending-approval
Rejected providers → /rejected-application
DashboardRedirect at /dashboard routes to the correct dashboard by role.

